==English==
===Phrase===
'''after the jump OR [[more]] [[after]] the [[jump]]'''
# "The jump" refers to a jumpline, the place in a newspaper article where the story is cut from a prominent page and the balance of the story continues on a page closer to the back. (e.g., From the front page, A1, to page A23.) Numerous studies show that the overwhelming majority of readers do not bother to follow the story past the jump line. It is a tool for allowing more stories to fit onto the prominate first few pages of a newspaper. Though it is most common in print media--usually newspapers--it has become common for online publications to include advertisments somewhere inbetween multiple parts of a story or to cut longer stories into multiple pages.

The phrase is often ironically or humorously used by the blogosphere to indicate information that will be added in later or further down the page. "More after the jump" is sometimes used in place of "more details below" or other synonyms.